  "text": "The cross-validation (CV) error relative to the length of the (111) reciprocal lattice vector for the experimental scans is shown in Figure 6 . When finding the disk locations in the thin region by cross-correlation, use of the bullseye patterned probe causes the mean CV error score decreases to 0.3% from 3.6%, an improvement of 12 times. In the thick region, the CV score decreases to 0.8% from 10.3%, an improvement of ≈ 13 times. While cross-correlation performs well when the pattern background (due largely to inelastic scattering) is low, hybrid correlation often better handles the 'plasmonic blur' in real samples [CITATION_1] . We repeated the disk finding procedure with p = 0.25 (Eq. 2), and the CV error decreased compared substantially compared to cross-correlation for the normal probes. However, in both the thick and thin Si wedge regions, the CV error ",
